Our nation stands at a pivotal moment as Parliament dissolves today to clear the path for the August 13 general elections, while international partners acknowledge the substantial economic progress we have made even as new fiscal pressures emerge. From the corridors of governance to our sports stadiums and mining communities, the stories of this day reflect a country navigating transformation, accountability, and the enduring spirit that defines us as Zambians.

## Main Stories

1. **Parliament Dissolves Ahead of 2026 General Elections**
   The National Assembly officially dissolved today, Friday 15 May 2026, in accordance with our Constitution, marking the formal end of the Fifth Session and setting the stage for our nation's electoral journey toward the August 13 polls. This constitutional milestone reminds us that our democratic institutions remain the foundation upon which we build our collective future as a people.

2. **IMF Acknowledges Zambia's Macroeconomic Progress While Urging TAZAMA Open Access Restoration**
   The International Monetary Fund has recognized that our nation has made substantial progress in restoring macroeconomic stability, with inflation falling to 6.8 percent in April, gross international reserves rising to $6.4 billion, and debt restructuring agreements now covering approximately 94 percent of the restructuring perimeter. However, the Fund has urged our government to restore the TAZAMA open-access framework for fuel imports, which had successfully reduced premiums by about 50 percent before its suspension following the Middle East conflict, and to publish the terms of emergency procurement arrangements as we work toward a successor Extended Credit Facility program.

3. **Electoral Commission Announces Campaign Period and Revised Nomination Dates**
   The Electoral Commission of Zambia has announced that official campaigns for our August 13 general elections will run from May 23 to August 12, with Chief Electoral Officer Brown Kasaro noting that revised nomination dates for parliamentary, mayoral, council chairperson, and ward councillor positions have been adjusted to May 20-22 due to delays in Parliament's adjournment. Presidential nominations will proceed as originally scheduled from May 18 to May 22, and the ECZ has clarified that the increase in polling stations to 13,529 reflects growth in our registered voter base to 8,786,300 citizens rather than the creation of new voting centers.

4. **Law Association of Zambia Urges President to Withhold Assent to Public Gatherings Bill**
   LAZ president Arnold Kaluba has called on President Hakainde Hichilema to withhold assent to the Public Gatherings Bill No. 71 of 2026, arguing that several provisions remain inconsistent with our Constitution despite introducing some progressive elements compared to its predecessor. The Bill, passed by the National Assembly on Tuesday amid stakeholder complaints that it was worse than the repealed Public Order Act, retains structural deficiencies including a quasi-permit regime and the criminalisation of peaceful assembly, reminding us that the quality of our laws shapes the character of our democracy.

5. **DEC Intercepts 150kg Cannabis Trafficking Operation at Kazungula Border**
   The Drug Enforcement Commission has arrested three individuals and seized 150 kilogrammes of high-grade cannabis concealed beneath sulphur sacks aboard a truck from South Africa at Kazungula Border Post, following a successful intelligence-led operation that uncovered 141 pre-packed parcels distributed across 10 bales. This interception demonstrates the vigilance required to protect our nation from transnational criminal networks that seek to exploit our borders and harm our communities.

6. **Anti-Corruption Commission Charges Businessman Over K80,000 VAT Fraud in Chipata**
   The ACC has jointly charged Lukomi Enterprises Limited Director Kopa Muyabala, aged 54 of Silverest Gardens in Lusaka, and his company with three counts of alleged unlawful acquisition of public funds charged as Value Added Tax, involving K80,000 in corrupt practices. This prosecution reinforces our collective commitment to ensuring that public resources serve the many rather than the few, and that accountability reaches every corner of our nation from Chipata to the capital.

7. **Government and UNDP Launch Digital System for Artisanal and Small-Scale Mining**
   The Ministry of Mines and Minerals Development, in collaboration with the United Nations Development Programme, has introduced a digital system to improve monitoring, productivity, and safety in our artisanal and small-scale mining sector, with Permanent Secretary Hapenga Kabeta confirming that the platform will track licenses, active miners, mineral production, employment including women and youth participation, and compliance in safety and environmental management. This initiative positions our ASM sector to capitalize on growing global demand for critical minerals while promoting local economic development and domestic value addition.

## Other Notable Stories

**Governance & Justice:**
* Political analyst Dr Neo Simutanyi observes that MPs changing constituencies ahead of the August 13 election, including Matero PF MP Miles Sampa shifting to Chawama or Lima and Monze Central UPND MP Jack Mwiimbu moving to Monze East, may reflect fears of defeat and unpopularity rather than strategic positioning.

**Energy & Infrastructure:**
* Energy Minister Makozo Chikote has bid farewell to his portfolio, expressing confidence that the new dawn administration has laid a strong foundation for our nation's energy sector with a vision to transform Zambia into a regional energy hub beyond merely ending loadshedding.
* Speaker of the National Assembly Nelly Mutti has commissioned a one megawatt solar photovoltaic plant at Parliament Buildings, describing it as a milestone in promoting sustainable energy and institutional resilience.
* Minister of Youth, Sport and Arts Elvis Nkandu has confirmed that army worm infestation at the National Heroes Stadium, where a $1.4 million rehabilitation is underway, is now under control following intervention by South African experts.

**Health & Public Services:**
* Minister of Health Alex Katakwe has received e-Registry equipment from the United Nations Population Fund for digitalisation of records management systems, emphasizing that this upgrade is critical to improving efficiency, accountability and service delivery in our health sector.
* Muchinga Province Permanent Secretary Tuesday Bwalya has issued a 14-day ultimatum to Nakonde District Hospital management to improve sanitation, noting that toilet facilities have been non-functional for some time.

**Technology & Development:**
* Minister of Technology and Science Felix Mutati has articulated Zambia's digital agenda as connecting remote villages, delivering power to clinics and enabling health workers to save lives through digital links, reflecting an approach rooted in learning and service.

**Agriculture & Food Security:**
* Central Province Permanent Secretary Milner Mwanakampwe has called for community mindset change to end hunger, asserting that hunger can only be overcome when citizens take responsibility rather than relying solely on external programmes.

**Sports:**
* Copper Princesses Under-17 coach Carol Kanyemba has expressed optimism ahead of the FIFA World Cup third-round qualifier against DR Congo, following a 1-0 practice match victory over Red Arrows women, with the first leg scheduled for May 24 at Levy Mwanawasa Stadium in Ndola.
* Red Arrows secured second place in the MTN Super League with a 2-1 victory over Green Eagles at Nkoloma Stadium, with goals from Angel Lubamba and Albert Kangwanda proving decisive.
* Zesco Ndola Girls captain Avell Chitundu has set her sights on the COSAFA Women's Champions League title after scoring twice in a 7-0 league victory over Luyando Foundation.

## Key Takeaways & Watchpoints

* **Electoral Preparedness:** With Parliament dissolved and campaign dates set, all eyes should remain on the ECZ's capacity to manage an expanded voter register of 8.78 million citizens across 13,529 polling stations, ensuring that logistical adjustments do not compromise the integrity of our August 13 democratic exercise.

* **Fiscal Discipline Amid Electoral Pressures:** The IMF's warning of intensified fiscal pressures ahead of elections, including weaker tax collection, pre-election spending, and agricultural subsidy overruns, demands close attention to whether our nation can maintain its hard-won macroeconomic stability without sacrificing long-term sustainability for short-term political gains.

* **Energy Sector Transitions:** As Minister Chikote departs and geopolitical tensions in the Middle East continue to affect fuel imports, the restoration of the TAZAMA open-access framework and the progress of our renewable energy initiatives, including Parliament's new solar plant, will be critical to whether Zambia realizes its ambition of becoming a regional energy hub.